{
 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "ced1f59c",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Automating a DWSIM Dynamic Simulation from Python\n",
    "## From GUI-based dynamic runs to scriptable process scenarios\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "### Overview\n",
    "\n",
    "Dynamic simulation is often associated with the simulator GUI: open the model, start the schedule,\n",
    "watch the trends, adjust the controllers interactively.\n",
    "\n",
    "That workflow is useful for exploration. But it becomes limiting when the goal is to run many scenarios,\n",
    "repeat the same disturbance case, generate data, or connect the simulation to a larger computational workflow.\n",
    "\n",
    "This notebook demonstrates how to take an existing DWSIM dynamic sample case and reproduce its behaviour\n",
    "from Python, without relying on the GUI scheduler.\n",
    "\n",
    "Python acts here as the **execution layer** around the dynamic simulation: it loads the case, resets the\n",
    "simulation clock, applies the pressure setpoint changes, advances the dynamic solver, triggers the internal\n",
    "DWSIM PID calculations, records the variables, and exports the resulting time series.\n",
    "\n",
    "The internal DWSIM PID controllers remain in place throughout. Python does not replace the control logic —\n",
    "it controls *when* the existing controllers are evaluated and what happens between steps.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "### Process Description\n",
    "\n",
    "The flowsheet represents a gas-liquid separator receiving a two-phase feed.\n",
    "\n",
    "```\n",
    "Feed ──► FV-01 ──► SG-01 ──► PV-01 ──► gas outlet\n",
    "  (stream 1)  (stream 2)  (stream 3)  (stream 4)\n",
    "                  │\n",
    "                  └──► LV-01 ──► liquid outlet\n",
    "              (stream 5)  (stream 6)\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "**Compounds:** Air, CO₂, Water, Methanol  \n",
    "**Property package:** Raoult's Law\n",
    "\n",
    "| Controller | CV | MV | Setpoint |\n",
    "|------------|----|----|----------|\n",
    "| PID-012 | Separator pressure | PV-01 opening | 2 bar |\n",
    "| PID-013 | Separator liquid level | LV-01 opening | 0.3 m |\n",
    "\n",
    "**Scheduled setpoint events:**\n",
    "- t = 3 min → PID-012 setpoint steps to **5 bar**\n",
    "- t = 10 min → PID-012 setpoint steps back to **2 bar**\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "### Prerequisites\n",
    "\n",
    "- [DWSIM 9.x](https://dwsim.org) installed on Windows\n",
    "- Python 3.x with `pythonnet 3.x`, `numpy`, `pandas`, `matplotlib`\n",
    "- Simulation file: `Dynamic Simulation - Separator Pressure and Level Control.dwxmz`  \n",
    "  (included with DWSIM at `C:\\\\Users\\\\<user>\\\\AppData\\\\Local\\\\DWSIM\\\\samples`)\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "> **Note:** The flowsheet is always reloaded from disk and the integrator clock reset to\n",
    "> `t = 0` before running, ensuring each execution starts from a known, reproducible initial state."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "cdd6003b",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 1. Setup — Load DWSIM Assemblies and Flowsheet\n",
    "\n",
    "We add the DWSIM installation folder to `sys.path` and load the required .NET assemblies  \n",
    "via `pythonnet`. Then we instantiate the `Automation3` object and load the simulation file."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "id": "ffb0e0ac",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Flowsheet loaded : True\n",
      "Dynamic mode     : False\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "import sys\n",
    "import clr\n",
    "\n",
    "# ── Paths ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n",
    "DWSIM_PATH = r\"C:\\Users\\<user>\\AppData\\Local\\DWSIM\"\n", #adjust user path
    "SIM_PATH   = (\n",
    "    r\"C:\\Users\\<user>\\AppData\\Local\\DWSIM\\samples\"\n", #adjust user path
    "    r\"\\Dynamic Simulation - Separator Pressure and Level Control.dwxmz\"\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "# ── Load .NET assemblies ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n",
    "sys.path.append(DWSIM_PATH)\n",
    "\n",
    "clr.AddReference(\"DWSIM.Automation\")\n",
    "clr.AddReference(\"DWSIM.Interfaces\")\n",
    "clr.AddReference(\"DWSIM.UnitOperations\")\n",
    "\n",
    "from DWSIM.Automation import Automation3\n",
    "\n",
    "# ── Load flowsheet ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n",
    "auto = Automation3()\n",
    "fs   = auto.LoadFlowsheet(SIM_PATH)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"Flowsheet loaded : {fs is not None}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Dynamic mode     : {fs.DynamicMode}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "e8263f29",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 2. Explore the Flowsheet\n",
    "\n",
    "### 2.1 Activate Dynamic Mode and Map Objects\n",
    "\n",
    "Setting `fs.DynamicMode = True` switches the solver to the dynamic integrator.  \n",
    "We then build a `tag → object` dictionary for convenient access throughout the notebook.\n",
    "\n",
    "> **API note:** Objects returned by `fs.SimulationObjects.Values` are exposed as  \n",
    "> .NET interfaces. Calling `.__implementation__` gives the concrete Python-accessible  \n",
    "> instance with all class-specific attributes."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "id": "61157fbe",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Tag              Type\n",
      "----------------------------------------\n",
      "PID-013          PIDController\n",
      "1                MaterialStream\n",
      "2                MaterialStream\n",
      "FV-01            Valve\n",
      "3                MaterialStream\n",
      "4                MaterialStream\n",
      "PV-01            Valve\n",
      "5                MaterialStream\n",
      "6                MaterialStream\n",
      "LV-01            Valve\n",
      "SG-01            Vessel\n",
      "PIT-01           AnalogGauge\n",
      "LIT-01           LevelGauge\n",
      "PID-012          PIDController\n",
      "IN-014           Input\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "fs.DynamicMode = True\n",
    "\n",
    "# Build tag → implementation dictionary\n",
    "objects = {\n",
    "    obj.GraphicObject.Tag: obj.__implementation__\n",
    "    for obj in fs.SimulationObjects.Values\n",
    "    if obj.GraphicObject is not None\n",
    "}\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"{'Tag':<16} {'Type'}\")\n",
    "print(\"-\" * 40)\n",
    "for tag, impl in objects.items():\n",
    "    print(f\"{tag:<16} {type(impl).__name__}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "21e8267f",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### 2.2 Inspect the DynamicsManager\n",
    "\n",
    "The `DynamicsManager` holds the integrator configuration (step size, duration) and the event\n",
    "definitions that describe what the dynamic scenario does: which objects change, at what simulation\n",
    "time, and to what value.\n",
    "\n",
    "We read these definitions here to understand and document the scenario. We do **not** execute them\n",
    "through the GUI schedule mechanism — instead, the setpoint changes are reproduced manually in Python\n",
    "inside the dynamic loop. This gives full control over when events fire and makes the execution\n",
    "order explicit and inspectable.\n",
    "\n",
    "> **API note:** `dm.RunSchedule()` is GUI-only and raises a `NullReferenceException` in headless\n",
    "> execution. Event IDs in `DynamicEvent.SimulationObjectID` are GUIDs, not tags — a lookup\n",
    "> dictionary is needed to resolve them to readable object names.\n",
    "> `DynamicEvent.TimeStamp` is the correct attribute for trigger time (`TriggerTime` does not exist)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "id": "bf2a0318",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "=== Integrator ===\n",
      "  CurrentTime     : 01/01/0001 0:20:30\n",
      "  Duration        : 00:30:00\n",
      "  IntegrationStep : 00:00:05\n",
      "\n",
      "=== Scheduled Events ===\n",
      "  t=01/01/0001 0:03:00  obj=PID-012  prop=SetPointAbs  value=5  enabled=True\n",
      "  t=01/01/0001 0:10:00  obj=PID-012  prop=SetPointAbs  value=2  enabled=True\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "dm = fs.DynamicsManager.__implementation__\n",
    "\n",
    "# ── Integrator ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n",
    "integ_key = list(dm.IntegratorList.Keys)[0]\n",
    "integ     = dm.IntegratorList[integ_key].__implementation__\n",
    "dm.CurrentSchedule = list(dm.ScheduleList.Keys)[0]\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"=== Integrator ===\")\n",
    "print(f\"  CurrentTime     : {integ.CurrentTime}\")\n",
    "print(f\"  Duration        : {integ.Duration}\")\n",
    "print(f\"  IntegrationStep : {integ.IntegrationStep}\")\n",
    "\n",
    "# ── Events ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n",
    "# Build GUID → tag lookup (SimulationObjectID is a GUID, not a tag)\n",
    "guid_to_tag = {\n",
    "    obj.Name: obj.GraphicObject.Tag\n",
    "    for obj in fs.SimulationObjects.Values\n",
    "    if obj.GraphicObject is not None\n",
    "}\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"\\n=== Scheduled Events ===\")\n",
    "for es_key in dm.EventSetList.Keys:\n",
    "    es = dm.EventSetList[es_key].__implementation__\n",
    "    for ev_key in es.Events.Keys:\n",
    "        ev      = es.Events[ev_key].__implementation__\n",
    "        obj_tag = guid_to_tag.get(ev.SimulationObjectID, ev.SimulationObjectID)\n",
    "        print(\n",
    "            f\"  t={ev.TimeStamp}  \"\n",
    "            f\"obj={obj_tag}  \"\n",
    "            f\"prop={ev.SimulationObjectProperty}  \"\n",
    "            f\"value={ev.SimulationObjectPropertyValue}  \"\n",
    "            f\"enabled={ev.Enabled}\"\n",
    "        )"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a9c8b896",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### 2.3 Inspect PID Controllers and Separator Initial State\n",
    "\n",
    "We read the PID tuning parameters and the initial process conditions directly from  \n",
    "the loaded flowsheet objects.\n",
    "\n",
    "> **API note:** The correct attribute for the PID setpoint is `SetPoint`  \n",
    "> (not `SetPointAbs`). Key attributes: `Kp`, `Ki`, `Kd`, `PVValue`, `MVValue`,  \n",
    "> `OutputMin`, `OutputMax`, `ReverseActing`, `WindupGuard`.\n",
    ">\n",
    "> CV/MV wiring is defined in `ControlledObjectData` / `ManipulatedObjectData`  \n",
    "> (object name, property name, units). `ControlledObject` and `ManipulatedObject`  \n",
    "> are `None` after headless load — in this sample DWSIM resolves the wiring  \n",
    "> at runtime via `ControlledObjectData` (no explicit assignment needed).\n",
    ">\n",
    "> `PROP_VA_5` is the valve opening percentage property."
   ]
  },
